{\displaystyle f\colon X\to Y}

, the domain of f is, by explicit definition, the set X. This isn't merely a characteristic or an emergent property discovered after the fact; in modern mathematical parlance, the domain is an intrinsic, foundational component of the function's very definition. It's not something the function *acquires*; it's something it *is* given at its inception. Without a clearly defined domain, the function itself is, strictly speaking, incomplete, like a script without a stage.

In the particular, and often more intuitively accessible, scenario where both X and Y are sets of [real numbers](/Real_number), the function f lends itself to a visual representation within the familiar [Cartesian coordinate system](/Cartesian_coordinate_system). When graphed, the domain of such a function manifests itself quite literally on the x-axis. It is depicted as the precise segment or collection of points that represent the horizontal extent of the function's graph, effectively acting as the projection of the entire graphical representation onto the x-axis. This visual aid clarifies which input values are 'active' or 'valid' for the function within that coordinate plane.

For a function explicitly defined as



